2026-07-10 00:52:49 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 00:52:49 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff', 'Legal_Agent'], 'text': ''}
2026-07-10 00:52:49 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 00:52:49 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff'], 'text': 'result from Legal_Agent\n**MEMORANDUM**\n\n**TO:** Procurement Department / Finance Operations\n**FROM:** Associate General Counsel, Cognizant India\n**DATE:** May 22, 2024\n**SUBJECT:** Legal Review: Payment Terms Deviation for M/s. Rashi Peripherals Pvt. Ltd. (Ref: \u20b92,32,332)\n\n---\n\n### 1. Contractual & Statutory Analysis\nThe proposal to deviate from the Master Service Agreement (MSA) standard payment terms (30-day credit) to an "advance payment" model introduces significant legal and financial exposure.\n\n*   **Contractual Breach:** Under the **Indian Contract Act, 1872 (Section 39)**, if the MSA explicitly mandates a 30-day credit cycle, unilateral deviation constitutes a variation of the contract. Without a formal **Addendum** or **Change Request (CR)** signed by authorized signatories, this payment may be categorized as an "unauthorized disbursement," potentially triggering internal audit non-compliance.\n*   **MSME Considerations:** Under the **MSME Development Act, 2006 (Section 15)**, Cognizant is legally obligated to make payments to registered MSME vendors within 45 days. While paying in *advance* satisfies the prompt payment requirement, it creates a "Prepayment Risk." If the vendor fails to deliver the goods/services after receiving the advance, recovering the funds becomes a protracted legal process under the **Arbitration & Conciliation Act, 1996**, often exceeding the value of the transaction.\n*   **Sale of Goods Act, 1930:** Advance payment shifts the risk of "Risk in Transit" and "Title Transfer" earlier than standard terms. If goods are damaged in transit, the vendor may argue that title passed upon payment, complicating claims for damages or replacement.\n\n### 2. Legal Risk Exposure\n*   **Financial Risk:** \u20b92,32,332 (Total liquidity exposure).\n*   **Operational Risk:** Lack of leverage. Once payment is made, Cognizant loses the "Right of Set-off" or "Right of Retention" usually available under the MSA for deficient performance.\n*   **Compliance Risk:** Audit findings regarding unauthorized deviations from the standard Procurement Policy.\n\n### 3. Legal Recommendations\n1.  **Maintain MSA Terms:** Adhere to the 30-day credit cycle as stipulated in the MSA. If the vendor insists on advance payment, perform a formal **Credit Risk Assessment** of the vendor.\n2.  **Bank Guarantee/Indemnity:** If an advance is unavoidable, demand a **Bank Guarantee (BG)** of an equivalent amount valid until the delivery of goods, or a formal Indemnity Bond.\n3.  **Formal Addendum:** If the deviation is approved, execute a written amendment to the MSA specifically for this transaction, clarifying that this does not constitute a waiver of standard terms for future transactions.\n4.  **Proof of Delivery:** Ensure the payment trigger is contingent upon a "Pro-forma Invoice" and a "Letter of Credit" or similar security instrument.\n\n---\n\n### LEGAL RISK RATING: MEDIUM\n\n**Advisory:** Proceeding with an advance payment without a corresponding security instrument (BG) or a formal contract amendment exposes Cognizant to unnecessary financial risk. It is advised to uphold the 30-day credit terms to maintain contractual consistency and leverage.\n\n**[Signature]**\n\n*Associate General Counsel*\n*Cognizant India*'}
