2026-07-10 01:35:05 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 01:35:05 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff'], 'text': 'result from Finance_Risk_Agent\nAs Senior VP of Finance & Risk Management for Cognizant India, I oversee the integrity of our financial operations. To ensure strict adherence to our fiscal governance framework, I have outlined the core pillars of our financial risk assessment and cash flow management below.\n\n### 1. Financial Risk Assessment & Control Framework\nEvery procurement request exceeding our baseline thresholds is subjected to a rigorous risk assessment. We evaluate vendor stability, compliance with the **Cognizant Code of Conduct**, and exposure to financial volatility.\n\n*   **Approval Thresholds:**\n    *   **Up to \u20b92 Lakhs:** Managed at the Business Unit (BU) Head / Director level.\n    *   **\u20b92 Lakhs – \u20b910 Lakhs:** Requires my (VP Finance) sign-off.\n    *   **Above \u20b910 Lakhs:** Requires mandatory sign-off from the CFO.\n*   **Risk Mitigation:** Any contract involving high-value assets (e.g., IT infrastructure) requires a **Vendor Risk Assessment (VRA)** to prevent procurement leakage and ensure alignment with our global procurement policies.\n\n### 2. Budget Head & Cost Center Allocation\nAll expenditures must be mapped to specific **Cost Centers** to ensure accurate P&L reporting.\n*   **Budget Head:** Procurement is classified under either **CAPEX** (Capital Expenditure for long-term assets) or **OPEX** (Operational Expenditure for recurring services).\n*   **Allocation:** Each request must cite the specific Cost Center code to facilitate monthly variance analysis against the approved Annual Operating Plan (AOP).\n\n### 3. Payment Terms & Cash Flow Management\nWe maintain a strict **Net-30 day** payment cycle to optimize our working capital.\n*   **Advance Payments:** As per Cognizant policy, advance payments are discouraged. If an advance is unavoidable (e.g., critical hardware procurement), the vendor must provide:\n    1.  **Bank Guarantee (BG):** Equal to the advance amount to mitigate default risk.\n    2.  **Exception to Policy (ETP):** Formal approval from Finance leadership detailing the justification for bypassing standard Net-30 terms.\n\n### 4. Regulatory Compliance & GST Liability\nAs a registered entity in India, we strictly adhere to the GST regime.\n*   **Tax Calculation:** For IT hardware (HSN 8471), we apply a **18% GST**. \n    *   *Example:* On a hardware procurement of \u20b910,00,000 (Basic), the GST component is \u20b91,80,000, resulting in a total cash outflow of \u20b911,80,000.\n*   **Input Tax Credit (ITC):** We ensure all invoices are uploaded to the GST portal to claim ITC, directly impacting our bottom-line cash flow efficiency.\n\n### 5. FY Impact (April – March)\nCognizant India operates on an April–March fiscal year. \n*   **Quarterly Budgeting:** We perform a "hard close" at the end of each quarter.\n*   **Accruals:** Any procurement initiated in Q4 (Jan–March) but delivered in the new FY must be accurately accrued to ensure the financial statements reflect the correct liability period.\n*   **Audit Readiness:** All documentation—including Ariba/Coupa approval trails, signed BGs, and ETP forms—must be archived for seven years to comply with Indian statutory audit requirements.\n\n***\n\n**Executive Directive:** Any procurement request submitted without the corresponding Cost Center code or the required level of approval (as per the \u20b92L/\u20b910L threshold) will be automatically rejected by the system. My office remains committed to ensuring that every Rupee spent aligns with our strategic growth objectives while maintaining the highest standard of financial discipline.'}
