entation of **Microsoft Purview (DLP)** to prevent unauthorized transfer of PII/PHI in alignment with the **DPDP Act 2023**.\n\n### 3. Regulatory Alignment\n*   **ISO 27001:2022:** Controls A.5.15 (Access Control) and A.8.1 (User Endpoint Devices).\n*   **DPDP Act 2023:** Ensures "reasonable security safeguards" to prevent personal data breaches.\n*   **IT Act 2000 (Section 43A):** Mandates implementation of "reasonable security practices" for sensitive personal data.\n\n### 4. Risk Rating: CRITICAL\n**Justification:** Given the nature of our delivery centers handling global client data, any deviation from these controls creates a high probability of data exfiltration or lateral movement by Advanced Persistent Threats (APTs). The financial and reputational impact of a breach is catastrophic.\n\n### 5. 72-Hour Hardening Action Plan\n\n| Timeline | Action Item | Responsibility |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **0-24 Hours** | **Inventory Audit:** Scan all assets in the DC via Intune/CrowdStrike to identify non-compliant/unmanaged devices. | IT Ops / Security Team |\n| **24-48 Hours** | **Containment & Remediation:** Isolate non-compliant assets from the production network. Force-push missing security patches and re-enroll devices in Intune. | Network Engineering |\n| **48-72 Hours** | **Access Review:** Audit all CyberArk vaults for standing privileges. Revoke all non-essential service accounts. Perform a final vulnerability scan via Nessus to confirm hardening status. | CISO Security Audit Team |\n\n**Final Directive:** All delivery center heads are required to sign off on the "Hardening Compliance Report" by EOD Friday. Non-compliance will result in immediate network revocation for the offending delivery center. \n\n*Stay vigilant. Security is a continuous process, not a destination.*'}
