2026-07-10 01:55:36 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 01:55:35 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff'], 'text': 'result from Legal_Agent\n**LEGAL ADVISORY NOTE**\n\n**TO:** Executive Leadership Team, Cognizant India\n**FROM:** Associate General Counsel, Cognizant India\n**SUBJECT:** Legal Liabilities and Disclosure Obligations regarding Unauthorized Disclosure of MNPI\n\n---\n\n### 1. Legal Framework and Liabilities\nThe unauthorized disclosure of Material Non-Public Information (MNPI) triggers significant regulatory scrutiny under Indian securities law. The primary governing regulation is the **SEBI (Prohibition of Insider Trading) Regulations, 2015 (PIT Regulations)**.\n\n*   **SEBI PIT Regulations (Regulation 3):** Strictly prohibits the communication of unpublished price-sensitive information (UPSI) to any person except for legitimate purposes, performance of duties, or discharge of legal obligations.\n*   **SEBI Act, 1992 (Section 12A and 15G):** Provides for stringent penalties for insider trading. Section 15G stipulates a penalty of up to **INR 25 Crores or three times the amount of profits made**, whichever is higher.\n*   **Companies Act, 2013 (Section 128 & 143):** Requires maintenance of internal financial controls. Unauthorized leaks may be construed as a failure of internal controls, potentially attracting liability under **Section 447 (Fraud)** if the disclosure was intentional and resulted in wrongful gain or loss.\n\n### 2. Mandatory Stock Exchange Disclosures\nUnder the **SEBI (Listing Obligations and Disclosure Requirements) Regulations, 2015 (LODR)**, specifically **Regulation 30**, Cognizant (as a listed entity\'s subsidiary/related party) must adhere to the following:\n\n*   **Immediate Clarification:** Upon the occurrence of a leak, we must verify the accuracy of the information and provide a clarification to the Stock Exchanges (BSE/NSE) to avoid market rumors affecting the scrip price.\n*   **Policy Compliance:** Under Regulation 9A of PIT Regulations, we must trigger our "Internal Control System" to identify the source of the leak and inform the Board of Directors immediately.\n*   **Disclosure of Investigation:** If an internal investigation is initiated, the nature of the breach and the remedial steps taken must be documented in accordance with our Code of Conduct to Regulate, Monitor, and Report Trading by Designated Persons.\n\n### 3. Legal Risk Exposure\n*   **Financial Exposure:** High. Statutory penalties under SEBI reach up to INR 25 Crores, excluding potential class-action litigation from shareholders if the stock price fluctuates significantly due to the leak.\n*   **Reputational Exposure:** High. Disclosure of a leak signals a failure in "Information Security Management" and "Corporate Governance," which may trigger an audit by SEBI.\n*   **Operational Exposure:** Potential for "Show Cause Notices" (SCN) from SEBI, requiring extensive legal resources to defend the company’s internal reporting mechanisms.\n\n### 4. Recommended Legal Remedies\n1.  **Immediate Internal Audit:** Initiate an immediate forensic audit of access logs to identify the source of the leak under the company’s Whistleblower Policy.\n2.  **Regulatory Filing:** Submit a formal disclosure to the Stock Exchange, clarifying the situation to neutralize market volatility, in consultation with the Compliance Officer.\n3.  **Corrective Action:** Issue a formal reprimand or terminate employment for the individual(s) responsible, ensuring compliance with the Indian Contract Act, 1872 regarding breach of confidentiality clauses in employment agreements.\n4.  **Strengthen Controls:** Review the "Chinese Wall" policy and implement stricter access controls on sensitive digital assets to mitigate future liability.\n\n---\n\n### LEGAL RISK RATING: HIGH\n\n**Conclusion:** The unauthorized disclosure of MNPI is a strict liability event. Failure to immediately address the leak and inform the exchanges will exacerbate the company\'s liability under SEBI regulations. I advise an immediate briefing with the Board and the initiation of a formal internal investigation.\n\n**[Signature]**\nAssociate General Counsel\nCognizant India'}
