2026-07-10 02:06:31 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 02:06:30 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff', 'Legal_Agent'], 'text': ''}
2026-07-10 02:06:31 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 02:06:30 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff'], 'text': '**LEGAL ADVISORY NOTE: BOARD ESCALATION PROTOCOLS**\n\n**TO:** Executive Leadership Team / Board of Directors\n**FROM:** Office of the Associate General Counsel, Cognizant India\n**SUBJECT:** Legal Implications of Immediate Board Escalation under Indian Corporate Law\n\n---\n\n### 1. Legal Framework & Statutory Compliance\nThe obligation to escalate matters to the Board of Directors is governed primarily by the **Companies Act, 2013** and the **SEBI (Listing Obligations and Disclosure Requirements) Regulations, 2015**.\n\n*   **Section 134 & 177 of the Companies Act, 2013:** The Board is responsible for the integrity of financial controls and risk management. Failure to escalate material breaches (e.g., systemic vendor fraud or catastrophic service delivery failures) can lead to personal liability for Directors under the "Duty of Care" doctrine.\n*   **Section 166 (Duties of Directors):** A Director must act in good faith to promote the objects of the company. Withholding material information from the Board constitutes a breach of fiduciary duty.\n*   **SEBI (LODR) Regulations, 2015 (Regulation 30):** For a publicly listed entity, the company is mandate-bound to disclose "material events" to stock exchanges. The Board must be apprised immediately to determine the materiality of any IT service delivery failure or contractual breach.\n\n### 2. Contractual & Vendor Risk Analysis\nWhen an escalation involves a vendor, we must cross-reference the **Master Service Agreement (MSA)** and the **Indian Contract Act, 1872**:\n\n*   **Section 39 (Anticipatory Breach):** If a vendor expresses an inability to perform, the Board must be apprised immediately to mitigate damages. Failure to act may waive our right to terminate for cause.\n*   **MSME Development Act, 2006:** If the vendor is an MSME and the dispute involves payment, the Board must be notified of the risk of mandatory interest (three times the bank rate) and potential public disclosure requirements.\n*   **Arbitration & Conciliation Act, 1996:** If the dispute is heading toward litigation, the Board must approve the legal strategy to avoid adverse findings that could impact our Indian balance sheet.\n\n### 3. Legal Risk Exposure (INR)\n*   **Financial Exposure:** Unmitigated contractual penalties and liquidated damages (LDs) for service non-delivery can scale into the range of **INR 50 Cr – 500 Cr+** depending on the client account size.\n*   **Regulatory Exposure:** Fines under SEBI regulations for non-disclosure can reach **INR 1 Cr – 25 Cr**, coupled with potential "debarment" or "cease and desist" orders against key management personnel (KMPs).\n*   **Reputational Risk:** Immediate Board intervention is the only mechanism to invoke "Force Majeure" or "Limitation of Liability" clauses effectively, protecting the firm’s valuation.\n\n### 4. Legal Recommendations\n1.  **Immediate Materiality Assessment:** Conduct a "Materiality Test" under the company’s internal Policy on Disclosure of Material Events.\n2.  **Formal Board Memo:** Draft a precise, factual memorandum detailing the breach, financial impact, and proposed mitigation (e.g., invoking the Dispute Resolution clause of the MSA).\n3.  **Preservation of Evidence:** Issue a "Legal Hold" notice to all relevant delivery teams to prevent spoliation of data, as per the **Indian Evidence Act, 1872**.\n4.  **Audit Trail:** Ensure all escalations are documented in the Minutes of the Meeting (MoM) to provide a "Business Judgment Rule" defense for the Board.\n\n---\n\n### **LEGAL RISK RATING: HIGH**\n\n**Advisory:** Escalation to the Board is not merely a procedural step; it is a statutory shield. In the event of a material breach, silence constitutes professional negligence. I recommend an immediate convening of the Risk Management Committee (RMC) to review the vendor\'s performance data against our MSA obligations.\n\n**Signed,**\n\n*Associate General Counsel*\n*Cognizant India*'}
2026-07-10 02:06:31 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 02:06:31 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff'], 'text': 'result from Regulatory_Agent\nAs the Chief Compliance Officer for Cognizant India, I have evaluated the requirement for an emergency board escalation. To provide a precise compliance roadmap, I have categorized the obligations based on the statutes governing a listed IT services entity in India.\n\n### 1. Regulatory Framework & Applicability\n\n*   **SEBI (Listing Obligations and Disclosure Requirements) Regulations, 2015:** Mandatory for listed entities.\n*   **Companies Act, 2013:** Governance, board meetings, and fiduciary responsibilities.\n*   **DPDP Act, 2023:** Mandatory if the escalation involves a Personal Data Breach.\n*   **CERT-In Directions (April 2022):** Mandatory if the escalation is triggered by a cybersecurity incident.\n*   **GST Act, 2017:** Applicable if the escalation involves financial transactions, service recovery, or liquidated damages.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Mandatory Reporting Timelines\n\n| Statute | Trigger Event | Deadline |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **SEBI LODR (Reg 30)** | Material Event/Information | "Immediate" (not exceeding 24 hours) |\n| **CERT-In Directions** | Cyber Security Incident | Within 6 hours of discovery |\n| **Companies Act (Sec 173)** | Board Meeting (Emergency) | 7 days notice (unless shorter notice is consented) |\n| **DPDP Act (Sec 8)** | Personal Data Breach | "Without undue delay" to Data Protection Board |\n\n---\n\n### 3. GST Implications (Financial Escalation)\n\nIf the emergency escalation involves a commercial settlement, penalty, or service adjustment:\n*   **HSN Code:** Generally **9983** (IT/Software Consultancy services).\n*   **GST Rate:** **18%** (9% CGST + 9% SGST for intra-state; 18% IGST for inter-state).\n*   **Determination:** \n    *   **IGST:** Applies if the service recipient is in a different state than the Cognizant branch providing the service (Place of Supply rules).\n    *   **CGST+SGST:** Applies if the service is provided and consumed within the same state (e.g., Cognizant Chennai to a Chennai-based client).\n\n---\n\n### 4. COMPLIANCE STATUS: ACTION REQUIRED\n\n**Current Status:** **ACTION REQUIRED**\n\n**Immediate Action Items:**\n\n1.  **SEBI Disclosure (Reg 30, Schedule III):** If the escalation concerns a material development (e.g., loss of a major contract, data breach, or leadership change), the Company Secretary must file a disclosure with the Stock Exchanges (BSE/NSE) within the stipulated 24-hour window.\n2.  **Board Governance (Companies Act, Sec 173):** If an emergency board meeting is required to address the escalation, ensure the meeting is convened with at least one Independent Director present (as per Schedule IV). Ensure minutes are recorded within 30 days of the meeting.\n3.  **Cybersecurity Audit (CERT-In):** If the escalation involves an IT security failure, the CISO must verify if the incident is listed in the Annexure of the CERT-In Directions 2022. If so, a report must be submitted to `incident@cert-in.org.in` within **6 hours**.\n4.  **Data Impact (DPDP Act, 2023):** If the incident involves unauthorized processing of personal data, the Data Protection Officer (DPO) must initiate a Data Protection Impact Assessment (DPIA) immediately.\n\n**Compliance Deadline:**\n*   **Materiality Disclosure:** No later than **[T+24 Hours]** from the identification of the material event.\n*   **CERT-In Reporting:** No later than **6 hours** from the identification of the incident.\n\n**CCO Directive:** All documentation regarding this escalation must be preserved for a minimum of **8 years** as per the Companies Act, 2013, to satisfy potential regulatory audits. Please provide the specific nature of the "emergency" to refine the tax and disclosure strategy further.'}
