2026-07-10 02:18:19 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 02:18:19 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff', 'Legal_Agent'], 'text': ''}
2026-07-10 02:18:19 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 02:18:19 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff'], 'text': '**INTERNAL LEGAL ADVISORY NOTE**\n\n**TO:** Procurement Department / Finance Operations\n**FROM:** Office of the Associate General Counsel, Cognizant India\n**DATE:** May 22, 2024\n**SUBJECT:** Legal Review and Advisory on Modification of Payment Terms with M/s. Rashi Peripherals Pvt. Ltd.\n\n---\n\n### 1. Analysis of Contractual Framework\nWhen modifying payment terms (specifically transitioning to or from advance payments) with M/s. Rashi Peripherals Pvt. Ltd., the following must be reviewed under the Master Service Agreement (MSA):\n*   **Change Control Clause:** Any modification to payment terms constitutes a material change to the MSA. This must be executed via a formal *Amendment* or *Change Order*, signed by authorized signatories, to avoid disputes under the **Indian Contract Act, 1872 (Section 62)**, which governs the novation, rescission, or alteration of contracts.\n*   **Performance Security:** If Cognizant issues an advance payment, we must secure a **Bank Guarantee (BG)** of an equivalent amount. Without a BG, the advance is an unsecured credit risk.\n\n### 2. Statutory Compliance & Implications\n*   **MSME Development Act, 2006:** You must verify M/s. Rashi Peripherals’ status on the Udyam portal. If they are registered as a Micro or Small enterprise, **Section 15** mandates payment within 45 days of acceptance of goods/services. Failure to comply triggers penal interest under **Section 16** (three times the bank rate notified by the RBI).\n*   **Indian Contract Act, 1872:**\n    *   **Section 39:** If we modify terms to include advance payments without proper safeguards, and the vendor fails to deliver, we may struggle to establish "anticipatory breach" if the contract is poorly drafted.\n    *   **Section 73:** Ensures our right to claim compensation for loss or damage caused by a breach of the modified terms.\n*   **Arbitration & Conciliation Act, 1996:** Any dispute arising from the amended payment terms will be governed by the existing arbitration clause. Ensure the amendment explicitly states that all other terms of the original MSA remain in full force.\n\n### 3. Legal Risk Exposure\n*   **Financial Exposure:** The primary risk is the "Default Risk" of the vendor post-advance payment. If the vendor enters insolvency, Cognizant’s claim for the advance payment will be classified as an unsecured debt under the **Insolvency and Bankruptcy Code (IBC), 2016**, resulting in low recovery probability.\n*   **Operational Risk:** Lack of strict "Delivery Milestones" linked to the advance payment may lead to supply chain bottlenecks.\n\n### 4. Legal Recommendations\n1.  **Bank Guarantee/Corporate Guarantee:** Do not release advance payments exceeding INR 10 Lakhs without a Bank Guarantee valid until the completion of the delivery/service period.\n2.  **Milestone-Linked Releases:** Structure the advance payment as a "Mobilization Advance" against a specific, non-refundable milestone, rather than a lump sum.\n3.  **Right of Set-off:** Include an express "Right of Set-off" clause in the amendment, allowing Cognizant to deduct outstanding advance amounts from future invoices if the vendor fails to perform.\n4.  **Due Diligence:** Conduct a fresh credit check and verify GST compliance (GSTR-1/3B filings) to ensure the vendor is not a "high-risk" entity under the GST Act.\n\n### 5. Conclusion\nModifying payment terms to include advance payments increases our legal risk profile. Ensure the Amendment clearly defines the "Conditions Precedent" to the release of funds.\n\n**LEGAL RISK RATING: MEDIUM** (Subject to the procurement of a Bank Guarantee).\n\n---\n\n**[Authorized Signature]**\nAssociate General Counsel\nCognizant India'}
2026-07-10 02:18:19 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 02:18:19 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff'], 'text': 'result from Finance_Risk_Agent\nAs the Senior VP of Finance & Risk Management for Cognizant India, I have reviewed the proposed advance payment request to M/s. Rashi Peripherals Pvt. Ltd. Below is the formal financial risk assessment and compliance audit.\n\n### 1. Financial Risk Assessment & Breakdown\n*   **Base Amount:** \u20b91,96,891.53\n*   **GST (18% on HSN 8471):** \u20b935,440.47\n*   **Total Payment Amount:** **\u20b92,32,332.00**\n\n**Risk Assessment:**\n*   **Approval Threshold Breach:** The amount of \u20b92,32,332 exceeds the \u20b92 Lakh threshold for VP Finance approval. This transaction cannot proceed without my formal sign-off.\n*   **Liquidity/Cash Flow Impact:** A cash outflow of \u20b92.32 Lakhs in advance negatively impacts our working capital cycle. Since this is an *advance* payment, we face "Counterparty Risk"—the risk that the vendor fails to deliver the IT hardware after receiving funds.\n*   **Policy Breach:** Standard Cognizant terms are **Net-30 days** post-delivery and invoice verification. An advance payment is a deviation from this policy.\n\n### 2. Budget Head & Cost Center\n*   **Budget Head:** IT Infrastructure / Hardware Procurement (CapEx or OpEx depending on the asset threshold).\n*   **Cost Center:** Must be mapped to the specific Business Unit (BU) or Corporate IT unit initiating the procurement.\n*   **Action:** The requestor must provide the Cost Center code (e.g., IN-XXXX) to ensure budget availability in the current FY.\n\n### 3. Compliance & Payment Terms Analysis\nTo proceed with this advance payment, the following mandatory controls must be enforced:\n*   **Bank Guarantee (BG):** Given the advance nature, Rashi Peripherals must provide a BG equivalent to the advance amount (\u20b92,32,332) valid until the goods are delivered and inspected.\n*   **Exception to Policy (ETP):** An ETP form must be filed in our Spend Management system (Ariba/Coupa), citing the business justification for bypassing Net-30 terms.\n*   **Approval Path:**\n    *   **VP Finance (Me):** Mandatory sign-off required (as the amount is >\u20b92 Lakhs).\n    *   **CFO:** Not required (as the amount is <\u20b910 Lakhs).\n\n### 4. Tax & Regulatory Implications (GST)\n*   **GST Liability:** The 18% GST (\u20b935,440.47) is applicable. \n*   **Input Tax Credit (ITC):** We must ensure Rashi Peripherals uploads the invoice to the GSTR-1 portal so we can claim the ITC in our GSTR-3B filing. Failure to do so will result in a cash loss of 18% on the transaction value.\n*   **TDS:** Ensure TDS under Section 194Q (Purchase of Goods) is applied if the aggregate purchase value exceeds \u20b950 Lakhs in the current FY.\n\n### 5. FY Impact\n*   **Cognizant India FY:** April 1 – March 31.\n*   **Impact:** This transaction will be recorded in the current FY ledger. If the goods are not delivered before the FY-end, this creates a "Prepaid Expense" on the balance sheet, which requires reconciliation during the year-end audit.\n\n### Final Recommendation\n**Do not process this payment yet.** \n1. The requestor must upload the pro-forma invoice and the ETP justification into the procurement portal.\n2. The vendor must submit a Bank Guarantee.\n3. Once the BG is verified by our Treasury team, I will provide the VP-level approval required to release the funds.\n\n**Status:** *Pending Documentation & Compliance.*'}
