2026-07-10 02:21:50 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 02:21:50 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff', 'Cyber_Security_Agent'], 'text': ''}
2026-07-10 02:21:50 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 02:21:50 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff'], 'text': 'result from Cyber_Security_Agent\nAs the CISO representative for Cognizant India, I am defining the security posture for the deployment of 20 Dell Latitude 5540 units in the Chennai delivery center. \n\nAdherence to these requirements is mandatory to maintain our ISO 27001 certification and ensure compliance with the **Digital Personal Data Protection (DPDP) Act 2023**.\n\n### 1. Risk Assessment\nFailure to harden these assets prior to deployment introduces the risk of unauthorized lateral movement, data exfiltration, and non-compliance with Cognizant’s "Secure-by-Design" policy. Unmanaged assets are primary vectors for ransomware and supply chain attacks.\n\n### 2. Mandatory Security Controls\n*   **Golden Image Deployment:** Deploy the standard Cognizant Windows 11 Enterprise "Golden Image" via **Microsoft Endpoint Configuration Manager (MECM)**. The image must be stripped of bloatware and have all unnecessary services (e.g., Print Spooler, SMBv1) disabled.\n*   **Asset Tagging:** Physical asset tags must be laser-etched/affixed. Digital tagging is mandatory via **Intune** (Device Category: "Corporate-Chennai-Laptop") and **ServiceNow CMDB** for lifecycle tracking.\n*   **Endpoint Protection:**\n    *   **CrowdStrike Falcon:** Must be installed and verified in "Prevention Mode" before network connectivity.\n    *   **Microsoft Defender for Endpoint:** Configuration profiles must be pushed via Intune to enforce ASR (Attack Surface Reduction) rules.\n*   **Encryption & Access:** \n    *   **BitLocker:** Full disk encryption (FDE) mandatory; recovery keys must be escrowed to Azure AD/Intune.\n    *   **CyberArk:** Privilege Access Management (PAM) agents deployed; local admin rights are strictly prohibited for end-users.\n*   **Hardware Security:** TPM 2.0 must be enabled in BIOS, with Secure Boot active and BIOS password protection enforced.\n\n### 3. Relevant Standards & Compliance\n*   **ISO 27001:2022 (Annex A 5.10):** Acceptable use and asset management.\n*   **Cognizant CISO Mandate:** Zero-trust architecture requirement for all new hardware.\n*   **India DPDP Act 2023:** Mandatory technical measures to prevent personal data breaches (Section 8).\n*   **IT Act 2000 (Section 43A):** Implementation of "Reasonable Security Practices" to protect sensitive personal data.\n\n### 4. Risk Rating: HIGH\n**Justification:** While the threat is currently localized to the Chennai facility, these devices will handle client-sensitive data. Without hardened configurations, the risk of data leakage or unauthorized access is "High" due to the sensitivity of the information handled by Cognizant associates.\n\n### 5. 72-Hour Action Plan\n\n| Timeframe | Action Item | Responsibility |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **0-12 Hours** | Physical audit, BIOS hardening, and asset tagging in ServiceNow CMDB. | Asset Management Team |\n| **12-36 Hours** | Imaging via MECM, Intune enrollment, and CrowdStrike Falcon deployment. | IT Infrastructure / Desktop Support |\n| **36-60 Hours** | Vulnerability scanning (Qualys/Defender) to ensure compliance with CIS Benchmarks. | Security Operations Center (SOC) |\n| **60-72 Hours** | Final audit report submission to CISO office and release of assets for deployment. | IT Security Manager |\n\n**Note:** Any device failing to report into the CrowdStrike Falcon console or failing to confirm BitLocker encryption status within the 72-hour window must be quarantined and isolated from the production VLAN. **No exceptions.**'}
