2026-07-10 02:26:51 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 02:26:51 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff'], 'text': 'result from Legal_Agent\n**MEMORANDUM: LEGAL ADVISORY**\n\n**TO:** Procurement / Finance Department\n**FROM:** Office of the Associate General Counsel, Cognizant India\n**DATE:** October 26, 2023\n**SUBJECT:** Legal Implications of Advancing Payment Terms for M/s. Rashi Peripherals Pvt. Ltd.\n\n---\n\n### 1. Contractual & Regulatory Analysis\nThe standard Master Service Agreement (MSA) typically mandates a 30-day credit cycle. Moving to an "Advance Payment" model constitutes a material amendment to the payment terms.\n\n*   **MSME Development Act, 2006:** If M/s. Rashi Peripherals Pvt. Ltd. is registered as an MSME, the **Section 15** mandate is to pay within 45 days. While advancing payment does not violate this, it triggers a shift in accounting and tax compliance, specifically regarding **TDS under Section 194C/194J of the Income Tax Act, 1961**, which must be deducted at the time of credit or payment, whichever is earlier.\n*   **Indian Contract Act, 1872:** Under **Section 62 (Novation, Rescission, and Alteration)**, any change to the payment terms must be documented via a formal Addendum or Amendment Agreement. Failure to execute a written amendment could lead to ambiguity in the event of a dispute regarding "consideration" and "performance."\n\n### 2. Legal Risk Exposure\n*   **Financial Leakage:** Advance payments increase Cognizant’s exposure to "Recovery Risk." If the vendor fails to deliver goods/services post-payment, our legal recourse under **Section 39 (Anticipatory Breach)** of the Indian Contract Act becomes harder to enforce without a specific "Refund of Advance" clause.\n*   **Audit & Compliance:** Deviation from standard procurement policies without a documented "Business Justification Note" may trigger internal audit flags regarding capital liquidity management and potential "Related Party" or "Conflict of Interest" scrutiny.\n*   **Exposure Valuation:** Estimated risk exposure is equivalent to the total advance amount (INR) plus potential legal costs for recovery under the **Arbitration & Conciliation Act, 1996**, should the vendor default.\n\n### 3. Recommended Legal Remedies\n1.  **Execution of Addendum:** Execute a formal Amendment Agreement explicitly stating the temporary nature of the advance payment and the revised payment schedule.\n2.  **Bank Guarantee/Indemnity:** For significant advance amounts, require a **Bank Guarantee (BG)** or a corporate indemnity bond from the vendor to secure the advance payment against non-performance.\n3.  **Performance Milestone Linking:** Ensure payments are linked to specific delivery milestones (e.g., Proof of Delivery or Bill of Lading) to mitigate the risk of "Unjust Enrichment" under **Section 70 of the Indian Contract Act**.\n4.  **Tax Compliance:** Ensure the Finance team updates the ERP system to account for TDS deduction at the point of advance, as per the Income Tax Act.\n\n---\n\n### **LEGAL RISK RATING: MEDIUM**\n\n**Advisory Note:** Proceeding with advance payments without a formal Addendum and financial security (e.g., BG) creates an unsecured credit risk. The legal department must review the specific "Advance Payment Clause" before the Finance team releases any funds.\n\n**Authoritative Signature:**\n\n*Associate General Counsel*\n*Cognizant India*'}
