2026-07-10 02:26:52 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 02:26:52 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff'], 'text': 'result from Cyber_Security_Agent\nAs the CISO representative for Cognizant India, I am outlining the mandatory hardening and asset-tagging protocol for the procurement of these 20 Dell Latitude 5540 units. Failure to adhere to these mandates will result in the immediate revocation of network access for these assets.\n\n### 1. Security Risk Assessment\nThe primary risks associated with new hardware deployment include **Unauthorized Asset Proliferation (Shadow IT)**, **Supply Chain Interception**, and **Data Exfiltration** via unencrypted local storage. Without standardized hardening, these endpoints act as entry points for lateral movement within the Cognizant corporate network.\n\n### 2. Mandatory Security Controls\nBefore these laptops are handed to associates, the following controls must be validated:\n\n*   **Hardware/Asset Tagging:** Physical Cognizant-standard asset tags must be applied to the chassis. The serial number must be mapped to the **Cognizant Asset Management System (CAMS)**.\n*   **Golden Image Deployment:** Deployment of the latest **Cognizant-approved Windows 11 Enterprise Golden Image** via SCCM/MECM. This image includes pre-configured security hardening (GPO lockdowns).\n*   **Endpoint Security Stack:**\n    *   **CrowdStrike Falcon:** Must be installed and verified in the "Aggressive" prevention policy mode.\n    *   **Microsoft Defender for Endpoint (MDE):** Must be active and reporting to the Cognizant security dashboard.\n*   **Encryption & MDM:**\n    *   **BitLocker:** Must be enabled with XTS-AES 256-bit encryption; recovery keys must be escrowed to **Microsoft Intune/Azure AD**.\n    *   **Intune Enrollment:** Mandatory enrollment for device management, compliance policy enforcement, and remote wipe capabilities.\n*   **Privileged Access:** Local Administrator rights must be removed. All administrative tasks must be routed through **CyberArk (PAM)**.\n\n### 3. Regulatory and Standards Compliance\n*   **ISO 27001 (A.8.1.1):** Requirement for inventory of assets and ownership accountability.\n*   **India DPDP Act 2023:** Mandates "reasonable security safeguards" to prevent personal data breaches. Improperly configured devices represent a failure to protect PII.\n*   **IT Act 2000 (Section 43A):** Cognizant is liable for compensation if we fail to implement reasonable security practices to protect sensitive personal data.\n*   **Cognizant CISO Mandate:** Strict adherence to the *Endpoint Hardening Policy (EHP-2024)* is non-negotiable.\n\n### 4. Risk Rating: HIGH\n**Justification:** New laptops are high-value targets for theft and unauthorized access. Until they are enrolled in Intune and the CrowdStrike sensor is heartbeat-active, they represent "blind spots" in our perimeter.\n\n### 5. 48-72 Hour Action Plan\n\n| Timeline | Action Item | Responsibility |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **0-12 Hours** | Physical asset tagging and registration in CAMS. | IT Asset Team |\n| **12-24 Hours** | PXE boot/USB deployment of Golden Image; verify TPM 2.0 status. | Infrastructure Ops |\n| **24-48 Hours** | Auto-enrollment into Intune; verify BitLocker encryption status and key escrow. | Intune Admins |\n| **48-60 Hours** | Verify CrowdStrike Falcon and MDE connectivity to the Cognizant SOC. | Security Ops (SOC) |\n| **60-72 Hours** | Final Security Audit: Run compliance report in Intune; verify "Compliant" status before handover. | CISO Compliance Team |\n\n**Final Directive:** The site IT lead is responsible for signing off on the "Compliance Readiness Checklist" for each serial number. Do not release these assets to associates until the Intune compliance dashboard shows a "Green" status for all 20 units.'}
