2026-07-10 02:29:26 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 02:29:25 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff'], 'text': 'result from Legal_Agent\n**LEGAL ADVISORY NOTE**\n\n**TO:** Procurement & Supply Chain Department\n**FROM:** Office of the Associate General Counsel, Cognizant India\n**DATE:** May 22, 2024\n**SUBJECT:** Legal Review: Vendor Agreement – M/s. Rashi Peripherals Pvt. Ltd. (Chennai Delivery)\n\n---\n\n### 1. Analysis of Contractual Clauses\n*   **Advance Payments:** Any advance payment clause must be strictly tied to a **Bank Guarantee (BG)** of equivalent value. Without a BG, advance payments constitute unsecured credit, exposing Cognizant to total loss in the event of vendor insolvency.\n*   **Time is of the Essence:** The MSA must explicitly state that "Time is of the essence" regarding the Chennai delivery schedule. Absence of this specific phrasing weakens our ability to claim material breach under the Indian Contract Act.\n*   **Liquidated Damages (LD):** Ensure an LD clause is capped (typically 10% of the PO value) to act as a genuine pre-estimate of loss, preventing the clause from being struck down as a "penalty" under Section 74 of the Indian Contract Act, 1872.\n\n### 2. Statutory Framework (Indian Laws)\n*   **Indian Contract Act, 1872 (Section 39):** If Rashi Peripherals fails to deliver by the stipulated date, this constitutes a "refusal to perform." Cognizant reserves the right to rescind the contract and claim damages for the breach.\n*   **MSME Development Act, 2006:** If the vendor is registered as an MSME, Section 15 mandates payment within 45 days. Failure to adhere triggers punitive interest at three times the bank rate (Section 16), which is non-negotiable.\n*   **Sale of Goods Act, 1930:** Under Section 31 and 32, delivery of goods and payment are concurrent conditions. We must ensure the contract stipulates that title and risk in the goods pass to Cognizant only upon physical delivery and acceptance at the Chennai facility.\n*   **Arbitration & Conciliation Act, 1996:** All disputes must be subject to the seat of arbitration in **Chennai**, governed by the substantive laws of India.\n\n### 3. Legal Risk Exposure\n*   **Financial Exposure:** Advance payments without a BG represent a 100% risk of capital loss in insolvency scenarios.\n*   **Operational Exposure:** Delayed delivery to the Chennai office poses a risk of business interruption. Total risk exposure is estimated at **INR [Insert PO Value]**, plus potential consequential losses which are typically excluded under standard MSA limitation of liability clauses.\n\n### 4. Recommended Remedies\n1.  **Bank Guarantee:** Mandate a Performance Bank Guarantee (PBG) for any advance payment exceeding 10% of the contract value.\n2.  **Termination for Convenience:** Retain a "Termination for Convenience" clause with a 30-day notice period to mitigate long-term exposure.\n3.  **Right of Set-off:** Insert a clause allowing Cognizant to set off any damages arising from delayed delivery against future invoices payable to the vendor.\n4.  **Force Majeure:** Strictly define Force Majeure to exclude standard supply chain disruptions, ensuring the vendor remains liable for foreseeable logistical delays.\n\n---\n\n### LEGAL RISK RATING: MEDIUM\n*Rationale: The risk is manageable provided that advance payments are secured by bank guarantees and time-of-the-essence clauses are clearly drafted to trigger specific liquidated damages.*\n\n**Authoritative Sign-off:**\n*Office of the Associate General Counsel*\n*Cognizant India*'}
