2026-07-10 02:40:04 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 02:40:03 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff'], 'text': 'result from Legal_Agent\n**MEMORANDUM: LEGAL ADVISORY**\n\n**TO:** Operations & Delivery Leadership\n**FROM:** Office of the Associate General Counsel, Cognizant India\n**DATE:** May 22, 2024\n**SUBJECT:** Legal Analysis of Liabilities and SLA Penalties – Incident INC2417058\n\n---\n\n### 1. Contractual & Statutory Framework\nThe analysis of INC2417058 is governed by the executed Master Services Agreement (MSA) and the governing Statement of Work (SOW). Under the **Indian Contract Act, 1872**, the following sections are paramount:\n\n*   **Section 73 (Compensation for loss/damage):** Establishes the right to claim damages for breach of contract, provided the loss arose naturally in the usual course of things.\n*   **Section 74 (Liquidated Damages):** Governs the enforceability of SLA penalty clauses. In India, courts will only enforce "reasonable" liquidated damages; penalty clauses designed to act *in terrorem* (as a punishment) are generally unenforceable beyond the actual proven loss.\n*   **MSME Development Act, 2006:** If the counterparty is an MSME-registered vendor, any delay in payment beyond 45 days attracts interest at three times the bank rate, compounded monthly.\n\n### 2. Analysis of SLA Penalty Clauses\nIn the context of INC2417058, the SLA penalty triggers must be evaluated against the "Service Credit" regime typically found in our MSAs. \n*   **Performance Breach:** If the incident resulted from a failure to meet defined Uptime/RTO/RPO metrics, the liability is capped by the "Liability Cap" clause (typically 100% of fees paid in the preceding 12 months).\n*   **Force Majeure:** We must verify if the incident triggers the *Force Majeure* clause. Under Indian law, the burden of proof lies with the party claiming the exemption to show the incident was beyond reasonable control.\n\n### 3. Legal Risk Exposure (INR)\n*   **Direct Damages:** Calculated based on the prorated service credits linked to the incident duration.\n*   **Consequential Damages:** Unless explicitly carved out in the "Limitation of Liability" clause, the risk exposure extends to potential claims for lost profits or third-party claims.\n*   **Regulatory/Statutory Risk:** If the incident leads to a breach of data privacy (Digital Personal Data Protection Act, 2023), penalties could reach up to \u20b9250 Crores, depending on the nature of the data compromised.\n\n### 4. Recommended Legal Remedies\n1.  **Cure Period Invocation:** Immediately trigger the "Cure Period" clause if the vendor/internal team is in breach, allowing 15–30 days to rectify the incident without triggering further penalty accrual.\n2.  **Mitigation:** Under Section 73 of the Indian Contract Act, the non-breaching party has a statutory duty to mitigate losses. Document all mitigation efforts taken post-incident INC2417058.\n3.  **Arbitration:** In the event of a dispute regarding the quantum of penalties, the matter shall be referred to **Arbitration under the Arbitration & Conciliation Act, 1996**, with the seat of arbitration typically being Mumbai or Chennai, as per the MSA.\n\n### 5. Formal Conclusion\nThe assessment of INC2417058 indicates that while SLA penalties are contractually binding, they must be proportional. We must ensure that the "Limitation of Liability" clause is invoked to protect Cognizant from unlimited liability claims.\n\n**LEGAL RISK RATING: MEDIUM**\n\n*Note: This memorandum is for internal advisory purposes and constitutes attorney-client privileged communication.*\n\n**[Associate General Counsel]**\nCognizant India'}
2026-07-10 02:40:04 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 02:40:04 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff'], 'text': 'To provide an accurate determination, I require the specific nature of incident **INC2417058**. However, as Chief Compliance Officer, I have outlined the regulatory framework and the decision matrix you must apply immediately to determine your reporting obligations.\n\n### 1. Applicable Indian Regulatory Framework\n*   **CERT-In Directions (28 April 2022):** Mandatory under Section 70B(6) of the IT Act, 2000.\n*   **DPDP Act 2023:** Obligations regarding personal data breach notification to the Data Protection Board (DPB).\n*   **SEBI (LODR) Regulations, 2015:** Specifically Regulation 30 (Disclosure of material events).\n*   **Companies Act 2013:** Section 134(3) regarding the Board’s report on internal financial controls and risk management.\n\n### 2. Mandatory Reporting Timelines & Triggers\nIf incident **INC2417058** falls into any of the following categories defined by CERT-In, you must report it:\n\n| Incident Category | Reporting Deadline |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| **Cyber Security Incidents** (e.g., Data breach, unauthorized access, malware, ransomware) | **Within 6 hours** of noticing the incident or becoming aware of it. |\n| **Material Event (SEBI)** (Impacts operations, reputation, or financials) | **Within 12-24 hours** (as per SEBI LODR Regulation 30). |\n| **Personal Data Breach (DPDP Act)** | As soon as "practicable" (Specific timelines pending DPB notification rules, but treat as immediate). |\n\n### 3. GST Implications (If the incident involves forensic/recovery services)\nIf the incident requires engaging external cybersecurity consultants to remediate the breach:\n*   **HSN Code:** 9983 (IT Software/Consultancy services).\n*   **GST Rate:** 18% (9% CGST + 9% SGST for intra-state; 18% IGST for inter-state).\n*   **Applicability:** IGST applies if the service provider is registered in a different state than the Cognizant entity receiving the invoice.\n\n### 4. Compliance Status Determination\n\n**ACTION REQUIRED:** Please provide the following details to finalize the status:\n1.  **Nature of Data:** Did the incident involve PII (Personally Identifiable Information)? (Triggers DPDP Act).\n2.  **Operational Impact:** Is there a disruption to Cognizant’s service delivery to clients? (Triggers SEBI LODR material event disclosure).\n3.  **Time of Discovery:** When was the incident first logged in the ITSM tool?\n\n#### Current Status Matrix:\n*   **COMPLIANT:** If the incident is a minor internal glitch with no data leakage or service disruption.\n*   **ACTION REQUIRED:** If the incident involves any unauthorized access or data exfiltration. **You must immediately notify the CERT-In portal (cert-in.org.in) within the 6-hour window.**\n*   **BREACH:** If the 6-hour window has already elapsed without filing a report for a reportable incident under the CERT-In 2022 mandate.\n\n**Immediate Directive:** \nIf this incident involves a breach of customer data or a ransomware attack, **do not wait for further analysis.** File an initial "Preliminary Report" with CERT-In to stop the clock on non-compliance, and simultaneously notify the Legal & Compliance Office to assess the materiality threshold under SEBI LODR.\n\n**Please provide the incident summary to confirm if the 6-hour window is still open.**'}
