2026-07-10 02:40:19 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 02:40:19 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff', 'Regulatory_Agent'], 'text': ''}
2026-07-10 02:40:19 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 02:40:19 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff'], 'text': 'result from Regulatory_Agent\nAs the Chief Compliance Officer, I have evaluated the scenario regarding **INC2417058** (Procurement Irregularity/Vendor Management Issue). Given the nature of procurement-related incidents in a listed IT services firm, the following regulatory framework applies:\n\n### 1. Applicable Indian Regulations\n*   **Companies Act, 2013:** Section 134 (Board Report), Section 177 (Audit Committee oversight on related party transactions and internal controls), and Section 143(12) (Reporting of Fraud to the Central Government if the amount exceeds threshold).\n*   **SEBI (LODR) Regulations, 2015:** Regulation 30 (Disclosure of Material Events/Information) read with Schedule III, Part A, Para A.\n*   **DPDP Act, 2023:** Section 8 (Obligations of Data Fiduciaries) – If the procurement irregularity involves the compromise of personal data of employees or clients.\n*   **CERT-In Directions (April 2022):** If the procurement issue stems from a cyber-attack on our procurement portal/ERP.\n*   **GST Act, 2017:** Section 16 (Input Tax Credit compliance) and Section 31 (Tax Invoice requirements).\n\n### 2. Mandatory Reporting Timelines\n*   **SEBI (LODR):** Under Regulation 30, if this incident is deemed "material" (i.e., impacts financial position or reputation), disclosure must be made to the Stock Exchanges (NSE/BSE) **as soon as possible, but not later than 24 hours** from the occurrence.\n*   **CERT-In:** If the incident involved unauthorized access to procurement systems, a report must be submitted to CERT-In **within 6 hours** of noticing the incident.\n*   **Companies Act (Fraud):** If the internal audit determines a fraud exceeding \u20b91 Crore, the auditor must report to the Ministry of Corporate Affairs (MCA) in **Form ADT-4 within 60 days** of their knowledge.\n\n### 3. GST Calculation & Compliance\n*   **HSN Code:** IT Services (Software/Maintenance) typically fall under **HSN 9983** (Other professional, technical, and business services).\n*   **Rate:** 18% GST.\n*   **Jurisdiction:** \n    *   **IGST (18%):** If the procurement involves inter-state supply (e.g., vendor in Karnataka, Cognizant office in Tamil Nadu).\n    *   **CGST (9%) + SGST (9%):** If the vendor and the specific Cognizant entity receiving services are in the same state.\n*   **Compliance:** Ensure the vendor has filed **GSTR-1** and the invoice is reflected in **GSTR-2B**. Failure to verify this results in the denial of Input Tax Credit (ITC) under Section 16(2)(aa) of the CGST Act.\n\n### 4. COMPLIANCE STATUS: ACTION REQUIRED\n\n| Action Item | Deadline | Responsibility |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Materiality Assessment** | Immediate (within 12 hours) | Legal/Compliance Dept |\n| **Internal Audit Review (Sec 177)** | Within 48 hours | Audit Committee |\n| **SEBI Disclosure (Reg 30)** | T+24 Hours (if material) | Company Secretary |\n| **Vendor GST Validation** | Ongoing (Monthly) | Finance/Procurement |\n\n**CCO Directive:** \n1. The **Internal Audit team** must immediately verify if INC2417058 constitutes a "fraud" under Section 447 of the Companies Act. \n2. If the financial impact exceeds the materiality threshold defined in our **Policy on Determination of Materiality**, the Company Secretary is directed to draft a disclosure for the Stock Exchanges immediately.\n3. Procurement must cease all payments to the involved vendor until the **GST portal validation** is completed to ensure no input tax credit loss for Cognizant.\n\n**Status:** **ACTION REQUIRED.** Please submit the preliminary impact assessment report to my office by 17:00 IST today.'}
2026-07-10 02:40:20 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 02:40:19 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff', 'Legal_Agent'], 'text': None}
2026-07-10 02:40:20 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 02:40:19 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff', 'Legal_Agent'], 'text': ''}
2026-07-10 02:40:20 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 02:40:19 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff'], 'text': 'result from Legal_Agent\n**MEMORANDUM**\n\n**TO:** Operations/Vendor Management Office\n**FROM:** Office of the Associate General Counsel, Cognizant India\n**DATE:** May 22, 2024\n**SUBJECT:** Legal Risk Assessment: INC2417058 – SLA Compliance & Vendor Obligations (Bangalore Hubs)\n\n---\n\n### 1. Contractual & Statutory Analysis\nThe engagement under INC2417058 is governed by the Master Service Agreement (MSA) executed between Cognizant and the respective vendor. \n\n*   **SLA Breach (Indian Contract Act, 1872):** Under **Section 73 and 74**, where an MSA specifies liquidated damages for failure to meet Service Level Agreements (SLAs), Cognizant is entitled to receive reasonable compensation. If the breach renders the performance impossible, **Section 39** (Refusal of party to perform promise wholly) allows Cognizant to rescind the contract and claim damages for non-performance.\n*   **MSME Compliance (MSMED Act, 2006):** Many vendors in the Electronic City/Manyata ecosystem are registered as MSMEs. Per **Section 15 and 16** of the MSMED Act, Cognizant is statutorily mandated to clear payments within 45 days. Failure to do so triggers compound interest at three times the bank rate notified by the RBI, which poses a significant financial risk during audits.\n\n### 2. Regional Risk Assessment (Bangalore)\nVendor operations in Electronic City and Manyata Tech Park are subject to high attrition and infrastructure dependencies. \n*   **Force Majeure:** Often, vendors cite "local infrastructure failure" (e.g., power grid issues or local unrest) as *Force Majeure*. Under Indian law, these are typically considered "foreseeable" in Bangalore and do not excuse SLA breaches unless explicitly defined as such in the MSA.\n*   **Risk Exposure:** Exposure is calculated based on the "Cost of Service Recovery" (CoSR). For high-criticality IT services, the risk exposure for INC2417058 is estimated at **INR 15 Lakhs – INR 50 Lakhs per incident** (inclusive of potential client penalties passed down to Cognizant).\n\n### 3. Legal Remedies\n1.  **Notice of Default:** Issue a formal "Cure Period Notice" as per the MSA, invoking the **Indian Contract Act, 1872** to demand rectification within 7–14 days.\n2.  **Liquidated Damages:** Enforce the "Service Credits" clause in the MSA to offset the invoice amount for the current billing cycle.\n3.  **Arbitration:** If the dispute remains unresolved, initiate proceedings under the **Arbitration & Conciliation Act, 1996**. Given the location, the seat of arbitration shall be Bangalore, with the High Court of Karnataka having supervisory jurisdiction.\n\n---\n\n### LEGAL RISK RATING: MEDIUM \n\n**Advisory Note:**\nThe risk rating is \'MEDIUM\' due to the potential for MSMED Act non-compliance if payment is withheld as a "set-off" for SLA breaches. **Do not unilaterally withhold payments** without a formal "Notice of Set-Off" drafted by Legal. Ensure all SLA breach documentation (downtime logs, ticket history) is timestamped and preserved, as this will serve as primary evidence in any future arbitration.\n\n**Action Required:**\n1. Verify if the vendor is MSME-registered in the Cognizant Vendor Portal.\n2. Issue a formal notice of non-compliance citing the specific SLA clause breached.\n3. Schedule a compliance review meeting with the vendor’s account manager.\n\n***Disclaimer:** This advisory is for internal corporate use and constitutes privileged legal communication.*'}
2026-07-10 02:40:20 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 02:40:20 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff'], 'text': 'As the CISO representative for Cognizant India, I have reviewed the incident report for **INC2417058** concerning the Bangalore procurement department. \n\n### 1. Security Risk Assessment\nThe incident indicates a potential breach of the **Principle of Least Privilege (PoLP)**. Unauthorized access to procurement systems exposes sensitive vendor contracts, pricing structures, and potentially PII (Personally Identifiable Information) of Indian employees or third-party contractors. The primary risks are:\n*   **Data Exfiltration:** Unauthorized extraction of proprietary procurement data.\n*   **Insider Threat/Credential Compromise:** Potential compromise of an endpoint within the Bangalore delivery center.\n*   **Regulatory Non-compliance:** Unauthorized access to records containing PII, triggering reporting requirements under Indian law.\n\n### 2. Mandatory Security Controls\nTo remediate and harden the environment, the following controls are mandatory:\n*   **Identity & Access Management:** Immediate revocation of the compromised service account or user identity via **Active Directory/Azure AD**. Enforce **Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)** for all procurement modules.\n*   **Endpoint Integrity:** Verify the workstation via **Microsoft Defender for Endpoint**. If the endpoint is non-compliant, initiate an automated **Intune MDM** remote wipe or "Isolate Device" command.\n*   **Privileged Access:** Ensure all administrative access to procurement databases is routed through **CyberArk** with session recording enabled.\n*   **Encryption:** Verify **BitLocker** status on all affected hardware to ensure data at rest remains encrypted in case of physical theft or unauthorized cloning.\n\n### 3. Relevant Standards & Compliance\n*   **ISO 27001 (A.9.2.2):** User access provisioning and removal of access rights.\n*   **Cognizant CISO Mandate:** Internal policy on "Data Handling and Classification" (Confidential/Restricted).\n*   **DPDP Act 2023:** Mandatory protection of PII; failure to secure could lead to penalties under the Data Protection Board of India.\n*   **IT Act 2000 (Section 43A):** Cognizant’s legal obligation to maintain "reasonable security practices" for sensitive personal data.\n\n### 4. Risk Rating: **HIGH**\n**Justification:** Procurement departments hold high-value vendor data and financial information. The risk is elevated due to the potential for lateral movement within the Cognizant network and the legal implications of the DPDP Act 2023 regarding the handling of sensitive personal data.\n\n### 5. 48-72 Hour Action Plan\n\n| Timeline | Action Item | Responsibility |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **0-12 Hours** | **Isolation:** Isolate the identified endpoint via CrowdStrike Falcon. Revoke all active sessions for the user account identified in INC2417058. | SOC Team |\n| **12-24 Hours** | **Log Analysis:** Pull SIEM logs (Splunk/Sentinel) for the last 72 hours to identify anomalous egress traffic or unauthorized file access patterns. | IR Team |\n| **24-48 Hours** | **Forensic Imaging:** Perform a remote forensic capture of the endpoint memory and disk to determine if malware (e.g., Cobalt Strike) was used for persistence. | Digital Forensics |\n| **48-72 Hours** | **Remediation & Report:** Patch vulnerabilities, force password resets, and issue a formal incident report to the Data Privacy Officer (DPO) for DPDP compliance review. | CISO Office |\n\n**Authoritative Note:** The procurement team lead is required to submit an attestation confirming that no unauthorized "Shadow IT" tools (e.g., unauthorized cloud storage or messaging apps) were used to process procurement data during this window. Failure to comply will result in further disciplinary action under Cognizant’s Information Security Policy.\n\n**Signed,**\n*CISO Representative, Cognizant India*'}
