2026-07-10 10:31:49 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 10:31:49 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff', 'PR_Comms_Agent'], 'text': ''}
2026-07-10 10:31:49 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 10:31:49 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff'], 'text': 'result from PR_Comms_Agent\nThis response addresses the reputational risk posed by the public escalation involving the CEO of Rashi Peripherals (a Cognizant partner/vendor) and the potential for negative spillover regarding Cognizant’s vendor management and professional standards.\n\n### 1. Reputational Risk Assessment: 4/10\n**Justification:** While the controversy is centered on the leadership of a third-party partner, the "guilt by association" risk is moderate. If the public perceives Cognizant as being silent or complicit in a partner’s toxic public behavior, it could impact our ESG ratings and employer brand. However, as this is a third-party issue, the risk remains contained unless it is proven that Cognizant leadership was aware of or enabled the behavior.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Holding Statement (For Media Queries)\n"Cognizant maintains rigorous standards for all corporate partnerships and expects our partners to uphold professional conduct that aligns with our core values. We are aware of the recent public discourse involving Rashi Peripherals and are currently reviewing our engagement protocols to ensure they remain consistent with our commitment to a respectful and inclusive ecosystem. We have no further comment on the personal conduct of individuals outside our organization."\n\n---\n\n### 3. Press Release (If required due to sustained media pressure)\n\n**FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE**\n\n**Cognizant Reaffirms Commitment to Professional Standards in Partner Ecosystem**\n\n**BENGALURU – [Date]** – Cognizant (NASDAQ: CTSH), a leading global technology services company, today reaffirmed its dedication to maintaining high standards of professional conduct throughout its global supply chain and partner network. \n\nIn light of recent public developments concerning the leadership of one of our partners, Cognizant wishes to reiterate that our corporate values—centered on integrity, respect, and transparency—extend to the organizations with whom we choose to do business. While we respect the autonomy of our partners, we are currently conducting an internal review of our vendor engagement policies to ensure that all associations continue to reflect our commitment to a professional and inclusive corporate culture.\n\nCognizant remains focused on delivering excellence for our clients and providing a supportive environment for our 340,000+ associates worldwide.\n\n# # #\n\n**About Cognizant**\nCognizant (Nasdaq-100: CTSH) engineers modern businesses. We help our clients modernize technology, reimagine processes and transform experiences so they can stay ahead in our fast-changing world. Together, we’re improving everyday life. See how at www.cognizant.com or @cognizant.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Media Outlets to Monitor\n*   **Economic Times (ET) Tech:** Monitor for industry sentiment and potential investigative pieces on vendor vetting.\n*   **Mint:** Monitor for analysis on how this impacts Cognizant’s stock/market perception.\n*   **ET Now:** Monitor for live broadcast mentions during market hours.\n*   **NDTV Profit:** Monitor for panel discussions regarding corporate governance and partner accountability.\n\n---\n\n### 5. CEO Internal Town Hall Talking Points\n\n*   **Setting the Tone:** "Our brand is built on the daily actions of 340,000 associates. We do not control the actions of our partners, but we do control who we choose to work with."\n*   **Professional Integrity:** "I want to be clear: Cognizant’s culture is non-negotiable. Whether it is an internal team member or an external partner, we expect professionalism and respect to be the baseline for all interactions."\n*   **Status of Review:** "The Corporate Communications and Procurement teams are currently reviewing our vendor ecosystem. We are committed to ensuring our partners reflect the same values we hold dear."\n*   **Call to Action:** "Stay focused on our clients. Do not engage in social media speculation regarding this matter. If you are contacted by the press, please refer them immediately to the Corporate Communications team."'}
2026-07-10 10:31:50 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 10:31:50 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff'], 'text': '**MEMORANDUM: LEGAL ADVISORY**\n\n**TO:** Procurement/Operations Department\n**FROM:** Office of the General Counsel, Cognizant India\n**DATE:** October 26, 2023\n**SUBJECT:** Legal Risk Assessment and Mitigation Strategy – Erroneous Breach Notice to M/s Rashi Peripherals\n\n---\n\n### 1. Analysis of Contractual & Statutory Implications\nThe issuance of an erroneous "Notice of Breach" constitutes a potential anticipatory breach or, at minimum, a "repudiatory act" if not handled correctly. \n\n*   **Indian Contract Act, 1872 (ICA):** Under **Section 39**, when a party has refused to perform its promise, the promisee may put an end to the contract. By issuing a wrongful notice, Cognizant may have inadvertently provided M/s Rashi Peripherals with grounds to treat the MSA as repudiated, potentially allowing them to sue for damages or suspend services without liability.\n*   **MSME Development Act, 2006:** If M/s Rashi Peripherals is registered as an MSME, any disruption caused by this notice—or subsequent withholding of payments—could trigger **Section 15-16** of the MSMED Act, which mandates payment within 45 days. Delayed payments attract penal interest at three times the bank rate notified by the RBI.\n*   **Reputational/Commercial Risk:** An erroneous notice damages the "covenant of good faith and fair dealing" implied in commercial contracts, potentially impacting future pricing and vendor cooperation.\n\n### 2. Legal Risk Exposure\n*   **Direct Damages:** If Rashi Peripherals suspends supply, we face operational downtime costs.\n*   **Statutory Interest:** If we withhold payments pending this "breach," we face 18%+ compounded interest under the MSMED Act.\n*   **Litigation Risk:** Potential for a suit for defamation or "tortious interference with business" if the notice was shared with third parties.\n*   **Estimated Exposure:** **INR 50 Lakhs – 2 Crores** (inclusive of potential litigation costs, service disruption penalties, and statutory interest).\n\n### 3. Recommended Remedial Actions\n1.  **Immediate Formal Retraction:** Issue a "Notice of Withdrawal" via legal letterhead. State clearly that the prior notice was issued due to a "systemic technical error" and is *void ab initio*.\n2.  **"Without Prejudice" Clarification:** Ensure all correspondence is marked "Without Prejudice" to prevent the erroneous notice from being used as evidence of a dispute in court.\n3.  **Restoration of Status Quo:** Confirm in writing that the MSA remains in full force and effect and that no payments are being withheld.\n4.  **Dispute Resolution:** Should they claim damages, invoke the **Arbitration & Conciliation Act, 1996** clause in the MSA to steer the matter toward mediation rather than litigation.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Formal Legal Advisory Note\n\n**LEGAL RISK RATING: HIGH**\n\n**Advisory:** \nThe issuance of an automated breach notice is a significant legal oversight. Under the Indian Contract Act, this serves as a formal communication that could be construed as a wrongful termination of the contract. \n\n**Action Required:**\n1. **Retract:** Send a formal letter of retraction within 24 hours. Acknowledge the error as a "technical glitch" to preserve the integrity of the business relationship.\n2. **Audit:** Conduct an immediate audit of the automated procurement system to prevent recurrence.\n3. **Internal Memo:** Advise the procurement team to cease all automated communications regarding breach/default until the system logic is vetted by Legal.\n\nIf M/s Rashi Peripherals initiates a legal response, do not engage in informal emails. Direct all correspondence to the Legal Department for review under the **Arbitration & Conciliation Act, 1996**.\n\n**Signed,**\n\n*Associate General Counsel*\n*Cognizant India*'}
