2026-07-10 10:41:08 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 10:41:08 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff', 'Legal_Agent'], 'text': ''}
2026-07-10 10:41:08 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 10:41:08 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff'], 'text': 'result from Legal_Agent\n**MEMORANDUM: PRIVILEGED & CONFIDENTIAL**\n\n**TO:** Procurement/Vendor Management Office\n**FROM:** Associate General Counsel, Cognizant India\n**DATE:** October 26, 2023\n**SUBJECT:** Legal Risk Assessment and Retraction Strategy: M/s Rashi Peripherals\n\n---\n\n### 1. Legal Analysis of Contractual & Statutory Standing\nThe issuance of an erroneous legal notice to M/s Rashi Peripherals (a significant IT hardware distributor) creates immediate exposure under the following frameworks:\n\n*   **Indian Contract Act, 1872 (ICA):** Under **Section 73**, an erroneous notice alleging breach where none exists may be construed as "anticipatory breach" or wrongful repudiation. If Rashi Peripherals suspends performance based on our notice, Cognizant may be held liable for compensatory damages for the loss caused by the wrongful notice.\n*   **MSME Development Act, 2006:** If Rashi Peripherals is registered as a Medium Enterprise, **Section 15** mandates payment within 45 days. Any legal posturing that delays valid payments exposes Cognizant to penal interest under **Section 16** (three times the Bank Rate notified by the RBI), which is non-waivable.\n*   **Defamation/Reputational Risk:** An unsubstantiated notice alleging breach of contract can be argued as damaging to the vendorâ€™s commercial standing, potentially triggering a tortious interference claim.\n\n### 2. Legal Risk Exposure (INR)\n*   **Direct Financial Exposure:** Potential interest liability under the MSME Act (compounded monthly) and legal costs.\n*   **Operational Exposure:** High. Rashi Peripherals is a critical supply chain partner. A supply stoppage would disrupt downstream IT delivery, leading to liquidated damages (LDs) with our own clients.\n*   **Estimated Risk Exposure:** **INR 50 Lakhs â€“ 2 Crores** (inclusive of potential litigation costs, interest penalties, and project delay penalties).\n\n### 3. Recommended Remedial Strategy\n1.  **Immediate Retraction:** Issue a "Withdrawal of Notice" letter within 24 hours to prevent the vendor from invoking the dispute resolution mechanism under the MSA.\n2.  **"Without Prejudice" Settlement:** Frame the retraction as a "clerical reconciliation error" to preserve our legal position while offering a direct meeting to clear pending invoices.\n3.  **Dispute Resolution:** Invoke the **Arbitration & Conciliation Act, 1996** (if necessary) only after internal mediation fails, ensuring that the venue remains per the MSA (typically Mumbai or Chennai).\n\n---\n\n### 4. Formal Legal Advisory Note\n\n**LEGAL RISK RATING: HIGH**\n\n**Advisory:**\nThe notice sent to M/s Rashi Peripherals is legally indefensible as it lacks the requisite evidentiary support for a breach under Section 39 of the ICA. Continued insistence on this notice will likely lead to an adverse MSME Facilitation Council filing, which is a summary proceeding and highly unfavorable to large IT service providers.\n\n**Action Required:**\n1.  **Cease and Desist:** Stop all further correspondence regarding the alleged breach.\n2.  **Formal Retraction:** Send a communication stating: *"We refer to our notice dated [Date]. Following an internal audit, we acknowledge that the notice was issued inadvertently due to a reconciliation error in our ERP. We hereby formally withdraw the notice in its entirety. This withdrawal is without prejudice to any future contractual rights."*\n3.  **Payment Reconciliation:** Expedite any pending undisputed payments to mitigate claims under the MSME Development Act.\n\n*Signed,*\n\n**Associate General Counsel**\nCognizant India'}
