licy. Provide secure VDI (Virtual Desktop Infrastructure) or browser-based access to company resources so employees can use personal hardware securely during the kickoff.\n\n### **Phase 3: Operational Adjustments (Hours 48â€“96)**\n\n#### **If Hardware is still unavailable 24 hours before kickoff:**\n*   **Modify the Agenda:** If hardware is limited, pivot the kickoff to "Workshop Mode." Use breakout sessions, whiteboard activities, and group-based collaboration instead of individual workstation tasks.\n*   **Hot-Desking/Shift Rotation:** Implement a 2-shift rotation. Group A uses the available hardware in the morning; Group B uses it in the afternoon.\n*   **Communication:** Send an immediate, transparent email to all attendees:\n    *   Explain the logistics delay.\n    *   Provide clear instructions (e.g., "Please bring your current laptop" or "Expect a modified, collaborative agenda").\n    *   Reassure them that productivity tools will be accessible via web browsers.\n\n### **Phase 4: Escalation & Recovery**\n*   **Vendor Accountability:** If the delay is caused by the vendor, initiate the penalty/SLA breach clause in the procurement contract.\n*   **Post-Mortem:** Once the event concludes, conduct a review to determine if the failure was due to procurement lead times, logistics, or vendor reliability. Adjust the "Lead Time" requirement for future hardware orders accordingly (e.g., moving from 2 weeks to 4 weeks).\n\n---\n\n### **Immediate Action Items for Today:**\n1.  **IT Manager:** Confirm if we have a local rental vendor on standby.\n2.  **Procurement Lead:** Get written confirmation from the current vendor by EOD.\n3.  **Operations Lead:** Draft a "Plan B" communication for attendees to be ready for deployment if needed by T-minus 48 hours.'}
