2026-07-10 22:21:32 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 22:21:32 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff', 'HR_Safety_Agent', 'Facilities_Agent'], 'text': ''}
2026-07-10 22:21:32 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 22:21:32 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff', 'HR_Safety_Agent'], 'text': 'result from Facilities_Agent\nTo address the theft of the CFOâ€™s laptop in Mumbai and ensure both security and business continuity, follow this immediate action plan.\n\n### 1. Immediate Security & Containment (Priority 1)\n*   **Remote Wipe/Lock:** Contact your IT Security/SOC team immediately to initiate a remote wipe or lock of the stolen device via your MDM (Mobile Device Management) solution (e.g., Intune, Jamf, VMware Workspace ONE).\n*   **Credential Revocation:** Force a global password reset for the CFOâ€™s corporate account. Terminate all active sessions (O365, VPN, SaaS applications) to prevent persistent unauthorized access.\n*   **Access Review:** Suspend the CFOâ€™s VPN access and physical building access badges immediately to prevent lateral movement if the device contained cached credentials or hardware tokens.\n*   **Legal/Reporting:** \n    *   **Police:** Ensure a local FIR (First Information Report) is filed at the nearest Mumbai police station (required for insurance and internal audit).\n    *   **Privacy:** If the laptop contained PII (Personally Identifiable Information) or sensitive client data, notify your Data Privacy Officer (DPO) to determine if regulatory breach reporting is required under Indian law (CERT-In).\n\n### 2. Physical Security Coordination (On-Site)\n*   **Mumbai Office Lead:** If you have an office in Mumbai, contact the **Office Manager or Regional Security Lead** immediately.\n*   **Incident Log:** Instruct local security to review CCTV footage from the time/location of the incident (if it occurred on company premises).\n*   **Escort:** If the CFO is in a high-risk area or requires a secure transit, coordinate with your regional security provider for a temporary security detail or secure transport.\n\n### 3. Logistics: Temporary Device Provisioning\n*   **On-Site Availability:** Check the local Mumbai branchâ€™s IT asset inventory. \n    *   *If available:* Have the local IT administrator provision a "loaner" machine. Ensure it is wiped, re-imaged, and has the latest security patches before handover.\n    *   *If not available:* Use a pre-approved local vendor or a "Hot Swap" partner to procure a replacement laptop. \n*   **Secure Handover:** Do not ship a device to an unverified location. If the CFO is at a hotel, have the device delivered to the front desk with a "hold for guest" instruction, or have a trusted member of the local IT/Security team deliver it directly to the CFO.\n*   **Identity Verification:** The CFO must verify their identity (via secondary device, video call, or government ID) before the new device is joined to the corporate domain.\n\n### 4. Communication Channel\n*   **Establish a "Secure Out-of-Band" Channel:** Communicate with the CFO only via a secure, verified mobile channel (e.g., Signal, encrypted corporate messaging) until the new device is set up. Do not send sensitive reset links to the potentially compromised email account.\n\n### Checklist for Local Mumbai IT/Admin:\n1.  [ ] File FIR at local station (obtain a copy for records).\n2.  [ ] Verify CFOâ€™s physical safety and location.\n3.  [ ] Check local IT spare pool for encrypted, pre-imaged hardware.\n4.  [ ] Provision device: Apply standard security policies + MFA.\n5.  [ ] Coordinate secure hand-off to the CFO.\n\n**Who is your primary point of contact in the Mumbai office?** If you provide the office location or the specific IT lead\'s contact, I can help draft a formal notification for them.'}
