2026-07-10 23:18:52 India Standard Time | INFO     | nsflow:_log:720 - nsflow - 2026-07-10 23:18:52 - generated/sentinel_crisis_command - INFO - {'otrace': ['Chief_of_Staff'], 'text': 'To manage this situation effectively, I have synthesized the insights from the Sentiment Analysis and Brand Safety agents into a strategic plan.\n\n### 1. Real-Time Monitoring Strategy\nSince I do not have a live, persistent feed of the Twitter (X) firehose, you should immediately implement the following monitoring protocol to track the interaction:\n\n*   **Search Query:** `from:rptechindia to:Cognizant OR @rptechindia @Cognizant`\n*   **Action:** Filter by **"Latest"** to capture new replies in real-time.\n*   **Key Indicators to Watch:**\n    *   **Response Latency:** A delay of >4 hours from Cognizant is a high-risk trigger for negative sentiment.\n    *   **Public Escalation:** Watch for the thread being picked up by third parties or tech influencers, which would necessitate immediate escalation to your PR/Legal teams.\n\n### 2. De-escalation & Engagement Responses\nIf you are managing the Cognizant account, your goal is to **acknowledge the issue publicly and move the conversation to a private channel immediately.** \n\n**DO NOT** engage in a debate, offer technical explanations, or use overly defensive corporate jargon in the public thread.\n\n#### Proposed Response Templates:\n\n*   **Scenario A: Initial Response (Acknowledge & Pivot)**\n    > "Hi @rptechindia, we sincerely apologize for the frustration caused. We take this matter seriously and are prioritizing a resolution. We’ve sent you a DM to gather the necessary details to assist you directly."\n*   **Scenario B: Follow-up (If the partner is still complaining publicly after a DM)**\n    > "@rptechindia, we understand your concern and our team is actively reviewing the details you’ve shared in our private conversation. We appreciate your patience as we work to resolve this."\n\n### 3. Brand Safety Guidelines\nAdhere to these rules to prevent the situation from escalating into a PR crisis:\n\n1.  **The "Move to Private" Rule:** Once you have acknowledged the issue and sent a DM, **cease all public commentary.** Do not reply to further provocations on the thread.\n2.  **Information Hygiene:** Never share ticket numbers, project names, or specific technical details in the public thread.\n3.  **Humanize the Reply:** Avoid generic, bot-like responses. Ensure the tone is empathetic and professional.\n4.  **Internal Alignment:** Before posting, ensure the response is cleared by your social media manager. If the issue relates to a security incident or high-value contract, **legal/compliance approval is mandatory.**\n\n### Next Steps\nIf you can paste the text of the most recent tweets from the thread here, I can provide:\n1.  A specific **sentiment score** (Positive/Neutral/Negative).\n2.  A **customized response** tailored to the exact nature of their complaint (e.g., service outage, billing issue, or supply chain delay).'}
